{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3209d90b-127c-4232-9da5-f8d1fcf02648","content":"For TUnit, tests are run via `dotnet run` and you can filter by class using `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe tree-node filter pattern is `Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches only tests in that class regardless of assembly or namespace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9e0ef5e8-7923-4e79-a89c-d411c3e259b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run only the SmsNotificationTests class from a TUnit project. TUnit uses `dotnet run` (not `dotnet test`) and has its own filter syntax.\n\nFor TUnit, the command to filter by class is:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nOr using the `--class` filter:\n\nTUnit uses a filter expression. Let me think about the correct TUnit filter syntax.\n\nTUnit's filter syntax uses `--filter` with patterns. To filter by class name, you can use:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --filter \"*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n\n\n```\n\nThe pattern follows the structure `Assembly/Namespace/Class/Method`, so I need to make sure I'm using the right number of wildcards to match the class name specifically.\n\n```\n\nI'm settling on the `--treenode-filter` option with the path pattern `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` to filter tests by class name in TUnit.","outputTokens":586},"id":"da93a14d-988d-4567-b1b5-5b8458b0fe3d","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:32:03.889Z","parentId":"b3bd6b16-03ec-49ad-98dd-26921a68178f"}
